<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25186i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25186i">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25186i"> 186(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> densified breath</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Tertullian denied the latter dogma, but (like Origen) he believed the soul to be corporeal, and he finally joined the wild revivalists of Phrygia, and credited the statements of a Montanist sister who had seen a soul&mdash;&ldquo;the <mark>densified breath</mark> of God in man.&rdquo; <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 309</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14126k" href="c14all.htm#c14126k">VI.C.14:126(k)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
